metadata.title: Cessna 150
aws::graph::propositions: Cessna 150 Model Configurations and Features
The 1959 Cessna 150 was offered in three configurations.
The Standard configuration was the most basic level with the fewest features.
The Trainer configuration was an upgraded version of the Cessna 150.
The Trainer configuration included dual flight controls.
The Trainer configuration included a more complete set of flight instruments for instrument flight rules operation.
The Trainer configuration included a radio.
The Trainer configuration included a landing light.
The Trainer configuration included several other features.
The Inter-City Commuter was the top-of-the-line configuration of the Cessna 150.
The Inter-City Commuter was often called simply the Commuter.
The Inter-City Commuter added an engine vacuum pump.
The Inter-City Commuter added vacuum-driven heading indicators.
The Inter-City Commuter added vacuum-driven attitude indicators.
The Inter-City Commuter added a revolving anti-collision beacon mounted on the vertical fin.
The Inter-City Commuter included all of the Trainer's features except for the dual flight controls.
All Cessna 150s for 1959 included a 20-ampere generator.
For the 1960 model year, the generator in the Commuter was upgraded to 35 amperes.
The 20-ampere generator was retained in the Standard configuration for 1960.
The 20-ampere generator was retained in the Trainer configuration for 1960.
The 35-ampere generator was offered as an option for the Standard configuration in 1960.
The 35-ampere generator was offered as an option for the Trainer configuration in 1960.
The Patroller configuration was introduced for the 1960 model year.
The Patroller configuration was introduced for patrol-type work.

text:
The 1959 150 was offered in three configurations; the Standard, the most basic level with the fewest features; the upgraded Trainer, with dual flight controls, a more complete set of flight instruments for instrument flight rules operation, a radio, a landing light, and a few other features; and the top-of-the-line Inter-City Commuter (often called simply the Commuter), which added an engine vacuum pump, vacuum-driven heading and attitude indicators, and a revolving anti-collision beacon mounted on the vertical fin, along with all of the Trainer's features except for the dual flight controls.
For the 1960 model year, the generator in the Commuter was upgraded to 35 amperes. All 150s for 1959 had included a 20-ampere generator, and this was retained in the Standard and Trainer for 1960; the 35-ampere generator was offered as an option for these configurations. Also for 1960, the Patroller configuration was introduced for patrol-type work.
